Complex Name: Cytochrome bc1 Complex (Complex III; Ubiquinol–cytochrome c reductase)  
Organism: Human  

Complex Function:  
This inner‐mitochondrial‐membrane enzyme catalyzes the oxidation of ubiquinol (QH2) and the reduction of cytochrome c, coupling electron transfer between respiratory complexes II/I and IV to proton translocation. - 10. 11 kDa subunit (UQCR11)

Complex Name: Synaptonemal Complex (SC)  
Organism: Human  

Complex Function:  
The SC is a tripartite proteinaceous structure that forms between homologous chromosomes during meiotic prophase I (zygotene–pachytene). It stabilizes pairing, enforces synapsis, and promotes crossover formation and recombination.  

Proteins and Corresponding Genes:  
– Lateral element proteins:

  • SYCP3 (Synaptonemal complex protein 3) – gene: SYCP3  
– Transverse filament protein:  
  • SYCP1 (Synaptonemal complex protein 1) – gene: SYCP1  
– Central element proteins:  
  • SYCE1 (Synaptonemal complex central element protein 1) – gene: SYCE1  
  • SYCE2 (Synaptonemal complex central element protein 2) – gene: SYCE2  
  • SYCE3 (Synaptonemal complex central element protein 3) – gene: SYCE3  
  • TEX12 (Testis-expressed protein 12) – gene: TEX12  
  • SIX6OS1 (Synaptonemal complex central element protein, also C14orf39) – gene: SIX6OS1  

Other Organisms:  
SC is conserved across metazoans and fungi. Homologs of SYCP1–3 and SYCE1–2 are found in mouse, rat, cow, chicken, zebrafish, and to a lesser extent in nematodes and budding yeast (functional analogs, not strict sequence orthologs).

Together, these effects integrate cardiovascular (vasoconstriction, heart rate) and immune (leukocyte trafficking) responses.
